title: For Sale:  A Letter From the Michigan State Police Regarding NEW PISTOL AR LAW
postcontent:
This is just a FYI for anyone out there that may be interested.

In April I purchased a 10.5" barrel AR pistol that came with a Sig Brace.  It took numerous attempts to register. The with the caliber written on the RI-060 as "Multi" from my FFL dealer.  They sent it back.  I contacted my FFL and they said they write that all the time and its fine so I contacted Lansing and they told me when they enter a caliber they don't have an option to enter "multi" so just write 5.56.  So I did and sent in the RI-060 again. Today I received a letter from the Michigan State Police Firearms Records Unit.  It stated that paperwork I submitted shows a barrel length of 10.5" and a overall length of 27.5".  This AR I bought came with a Flash suppressor and a Sig Brace on it.  So my FFL measured from front to back which was 27.5".
This letter states that MCL 28.421 (1) (e) of the Michigan Firearms Act has recently changed and now defines a "Pistol" as a firearm 26" or less, previously 28" I believe.
So this letter stated that since my firearm was above 26" it was not considered a pistol and therefore no registration was required and this registration will be removed from their database.
Also when I was talking to my FFL he told me that the firearm should be measured without the Sig brace on it (someone that works there screwed up) and if the muzzle break was not pinned or permanent, if it had a threaded one it should be measured to the end of the threads and not the end of the muzzle break which would take my overall measurement far below 26 inches therefore keeping classified as a pistol.
That doesn't make much sense to me but that's what he said. He said they are both parts that come off and are not necessarily part of the rifle so we do not need to include them in the overall measurement. 
Thanks Dan



I am still a little confused by this.  I asked my FFL, well then , wouldn't now be considered a Short Barreled Rifle (SBR)?  He said no be cause of the length.  So what exactly is the definition of an SBR now? That was the part I did not understand.  
Maybe someone with more knowledge than me can clarify this?

Thanks

Certainly one of the most unusual-looking guns to come out is the Mossberg 500 Chainsaw. Built in the iconic Mossberg 500 action, the Chainsaw is a pistol-grip pump-action shotgun with no stock. While guns like this are desirable for home defense, they're notoriously hard to control while firing, a problem that Mossberg has solved by attaching a wrap-around chainsaw-style hand grip to the pump. Intended to be fired from the hip, this top handle allows the user to cycle the action while simultaneously maintaining leverage above the gun to help tame muzzle flip. In addition to the chainsaw-style grip, the 500 Chainsaw has a stand-off barrel that can be used to breech doors and three rails that can mount accessories.
